        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We make sensitive measurements of H2O maser emission at Band 8 with a continuous wide velocity coverage that includes blue- and red-shifted velocity components w.r.t. the galaxy's systemic velocities. 
Doppler-shifted 22 GHz ¥ho maser lines that are usually observed over velocity range of approximately 500 -1,000 ¥km¥ w.r.t the systemic velocity, which will be covered by wide velocity range of the ALMA correlator. Configuring two basebands (Baseband-1 and -2) with 1875 MHz (or  1290 km/s at 439 GHz) bandwidth and 960 spectral channels will yield a spectral resolution of 1.93~MHz (1.3 km/s), which will accommodate maser lines including highly Doppler-shifted maser lines. This spectral setup will be sufficient for detecting and studying the nature of weak and narrow maser lines. 

Proposed observations consist of one track for each source at each frequency band preferably in the most extended configuration in order to measure source brightness temperature and position of the maser lines.

Rms sensitivity of 25 mJy to detect line emission (Sp~120 mJy) is justified in the science case document. Both integration time and total observation time required to complete this program are estimated by OT and are all listed in Table 2 in the science case.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
