            <prj:justificationText>We make sensitive measurements of H2O maser emission at 325 GHz (Band 7) with a continuous wide velocity coverage that includes blue- and red-shifted velocity components w.r.t. the galaxy's systemic velocities. Doppler-shifted 22 GHz ¥ho maser lines that are usually observed over velocity range of approximately 500-1000 km/s w.r.t the systemic velocity, which will be covered by wide velocity range of the ALMA correlator. Configuring two base bands (Baseband-1 and -2) with 1875 MHz (or 1740 km/s) bandwidth and 960 spectral channels will yield a spectral resolution of 1.93 MHz (1.8 km/s), which will accommodate maser lines including highly Doppler-shifted (redshifts up to ~2500 km/s) maser lines. The third baseband (Baseband-3) setup is utilized to allocate vibrationally excited H2O emission in the 336.228 GHz transition that happens to fall in the opposite side band of the 325 GHz. This spectral setup will be sufficient for detecting and studying the nature of weak and narrow maser lines. 


Proposed observations consist of one track for each source at each frequency band preferably in the most extended configuration in order to measure source brightness temperature and position of the maser lines.

Required rms sensitivity (20 mJy) at the given frequency resolution is justified in the science case document. Both integration time and total observation time required to complete this program are estimated by OT and they are listed in Table 2 in the science case text.
</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
