    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>In the ALMA Cycle 0 observation, we discovered H2O maser line in the 321 GHz transition towards the southern nearby AGN, Circinus galaxy. The discovery of this extragalactic sub-mm H2O maser line has been long sought and could be important for probing the gas dynamics and conditions closer to central engine of AGN. In the ALMA observation, a highly Doppler-shifted feature of the 321 GHz H2O maser (redshifts up to 635 km/s) was marginally detected. Assuming that this high-velocity feature arises from a Keplerian rotating disk imaged by VLBI observations of 22 GHz H2O, it locates at r~0.02 pc, which might probe molecular material closest to central engine. In this proposal, we follow up our discovery and aim at more detection of the H2O lines in higher velocities with both more sensitivity and new transitions (325.153 GHz and 439.151 GHz) to explore inner part of a nuclear disk that is not traced by 22 GHz maser. Thus, sub-mm H2O maser could be used as probes of dynamics, physical conditions, potentially as probes of the magnetic field. The sub-mm masers can be used as a cosmological tool for H0 determination with future sub-mm VLBI using the ongoing phasing-ALMA project.
</prp:abstract>
